set.seed(4200)
my_sample<-sample(241600, 50000)

sgemm = read_csv("sgemm_product.csv")
## Parsed with column specification:
## cols(
##   MWG = col_double(),
##   NWG = col_double(),
##   KWG = col_double(),
##   MDIMC = col_double(),
##   NDIMC = col_double(),
##   MDIMA = col_double(),
##   NDIMB = col_double(),
##   KWI = col_double(),
##   VWM = col_double(),
##   VWN = col_double(),
##   STRM = col_double(),
##   STRN = col_double(),
##   SA = col_double(),
##   SB = col_double(),
##   `Run1 (ms)` = col_double(),
##   `Run2 (ms)` = col_double(),
##   `Run3 (ms)` = col_double(),
##   `Run4 (ms)` = col_double()
## )
sgemm = sgemm %>% 
  rename(Run1 = "Run1 (ms)", Run2 = "Run2 (ms)", Run3 = "Run3 (ms)", Run4 = "Run4 (ms)")
sgemm = sgemm %>%
  mutate(logrun1 = log(Run1)) %>%
  select(-Run1, -Run2, -Run3, -Run4)
means = apply(sgemm, 2, mean)
std = apply(sgemm, 2, sd)
sgemm_scaled = scale(sgemm, center = means, scale = std)

sgemm_x = sgemm_scaled[,-15]
sgemm_y = sgemm_scaled[,15]

1) Fit a network with one hidden layer, 8 nodes, ReLU activation, and squared error loss to predict the log times from Run 1. Compare to the results from Lab 3

model_1 <- keras_model_sequential()
model_1 %>%
    layer_dense(units = 8, activation = "relu", input_shape = c(14)) %>%
    layer_dense(units = 1)
summary(model_1)
## Model: "sequential"
## ________________________________________________________________________________
## Layer (type)                        Output Shape                    Param #     
## ================================================================================
## dense (Dense)                       (None, 8)                       120         
## ________________________________________________________________________________
## dense_1 (Dense)                     (None, 1)                       9           
## ================================================================================
## Total params: 129
## Trainable params: 129
## Non-trainable params: 0
## ________________________________________________________________________________
model_1 %>% compile(
    optimizer = "rmsprop",
    loss = "mse",
    metrics = c("mae") 
)
history <- model_1 %>% fit(
    sgemm_x, sgemm_y,
    batch_size = 100,
    epochs = 60,
    verbose = 1
)

plot(history)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'

2) Add a second hidden layer after the first with 4 nodes and repeat part 1

model_1 <- keras_model_sequential()
model_1 %>%
    layer_dense(units = 8, activation = "relu", input_shape = c(14)) %>%
    layer_dense(units = 4, activation = "relu") %>%
    layer_dense(units = 1)
summary(model_1)
## Model: "sequential_1"
## ________________________________________________________________________________
## Layer (type)                        Output Shape                    Param #     
## ================================================================================
## dense_2 (Dense)                     (None, 8)                       120         
## ________________________________________________________________________________
## dense_3 (Dense)                     (None, 4)                       36          
## ________________________________________________________________________________
## dense_4 (Dense)                     (None, 1)                       5           
## ================================================================================
## Total params: 161
## Trainable params: 161
## Non-trainable params: 0
## ________________________________________________________________________________
model_1 %>% compile(
    optimizer = "rmsprop",
    loss = "mse",
    metrics = c("mae") 
)
history <- model_1 %>% fit(
    sgemm_x, sgemm_y,
    batch_size = 100,
    epochs = 60,
    verbose = 1
)

plot(history)
## `geom_smooth()` using formula 'y ~ x'
